# Security & Authentication Patterns

## Authentication
- Use JWT with short-lived access tokens (15 min) and long-lived refresh tokens (7 days)
- Store refresh tokens server-side with revocation capability
- Never store tokens in localStorage — use httpOnly secure cookies
- Implement token rotation on refresh

## Authorization
- Use RBAC (Role-Based Access Control) with middleware guards
- Define permissions per route, not per controller
- Check ownership for resource-level access (users can only modify their own data)

## Secrets
- Never hardcode secrets, API keys, or credentials
- Use environment variables loaded via validated config module
- Rotate secrets quarterly
- Use Azure Key Vault or similar for production secrets

## Input Validation
- Validate and sanitize ALL user inputs at API boundary
- Use parameterized queries only — never string concatenation for SQL
- Apply Content Security Policy headers
- Enable CORS with explicit origin allowlist

## Logging
- Never log passwords, tokens, PII, or credit card numbers
- Log authentication events (login, logout, failed attempts)
- Use structured JSON logging with correlation IDs
